    Announcement: "Post:12 A slotted ALOHA network"

    Dr.KAPIL NETAJI VHATKAR
    Created Aug 10Aug 10 Deleted
    This post is visible to all teachers in this class. It will be permanently deleted today.
    Post:12
    A slotted ALOHA network transmits 200-bit frames using a shared channel with a 200-kbps
    bandwidth. Find the throughput if the system (all stations together) produces
    a. 1000 frames per second.
    b. 500 frames per second.
    c. 250 frames per second.

    Answer:- 

    Useful formulae,
    • Frame-Transmission Time = (Frame-size) / (Bandwidth)-----------(1)
    • Throughput, S= G * e^(-G)--------------------------------------(2)
    • G=(Number of frames produced by the system) * (Frame-Transmission Time)--------------(3)
    Given data,
    • Frame-size=200 bits.
    • Bandwidth=200 kbps =200* 10^3 bps.
    So, 
    • Frame-Transmission-Time=(200)/(200*10^3) = 10^-3 seconds.
    a) In this case, system produces 1000 frames
    • So, G=1000 * 10^-3=1
    • Throughput, S=1 * e^(-1) = 0.368  (Or 36.8 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 1000*0.368=368.
    • Only 368 frames out of 1000 frames will survive.
    b) In this case, system produces 500 frames
    • So, G=500 * 10^-3=0.5
    • Throughput, S=0.5 * e^(-0.5) = 0.303  (Or 30.3 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 500*0.303=151.
    • Only 151 frames out of 500 frames will survive.
    c) In this case, system produces 250 frames

    • So, G=250 * 10^-3=0.25
    • Throughput, S=0.25 * e^(-0.25) = 0.195  (Or 19.5 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 250*0.195 =49.
    • Only 49 frames out of 250 frames will survive.

    Announcement: "Post 11: Example on pure ALOHA A pure"

    Dr.KAPIL NETAJI VHATKAR
    Created Aug 10Aug 10 Deleted
    This post is visible to all teachers in this class. It will be permanently deleted today.
    Post 11:
    Example on pure ALOHA
    A pure ALOHA network transmits 200-bit frames on a shared channel of 200 kbps. What is the throughput if the system (all stations together) produces
    a. 1000 frames per second?
    b. 500 frames per second?
    c. 250 frames per second?


    Answer:- 

    Useful formulae,
    • Frame-Transmission Time = (Frame-size) / (Bandwidth)-----------(1)
    • Throughput, S= G * e^(-2G)--------------------------------------(2)
    • G=(Number of frames produced by the system) * (Frame-Transmission Time)--------------(3)
    Given data,
    • Frame-size=200 bits.
    • Bandwidth=200 kbps =200* 10^3 bps.
    So, 
    • Frame-Transmission-Time=(200)/(200*10^3) = 10^-3 seconds.
    a) In this case, system produces 1000 frames
    • So, G=1000 * 10^-3=1
    • Throughput, S=1 * e^(-2*1) = 0.135  (Or 13.5 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 1000*0.135=135.
    • Only 135 frames out of 1000 frames will survive.
    b) In this case, system produces 500 frames
    • So, G=500 * 10^-3=0.5
    • Throughput, S=0.5 * e^(-2*0.5) = 0.184  (Or 18.4 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 500*0.184=92.
    • Only 92 frames out of 500 frames will survive.
    c) In this case, system produces 250 frames

    • So, G=250 * 10^-3=0.25
    • Throughput, S=0.25 * e^(-2*0.25) = 0.152  (Or 15.2 %)
    • Therefore Throughput is 250*0.152 =38.
    • Only 38 frames out of 250 frames will survive.

    Announcement: "Post: 8 Cyclic Redundancy Check (CRC)"

    Dr.KAPIL NETAJI VHATKAR
    Created Aug 10Aug 10 Deleted
    This post is visible to all teachers in this class. It will be permanently deleted today.
    Post: 8
    Cyclic Redundancy Check (CRC)

    CRC-Cyclic Redundancy Check is an error detection method.

    Sender Side Steps of CRC
    1) Find the length (L) of the divisor
    2) Append 'L-1' bits to the original message
    3) Perform binary division operation.
    4) Remainder of the divison = CRC
    5) Data Transmitted=Original-Message + CRC

    Receiver Side Steps of CRC
    1) Find the length(L) of the divisor
    2) Perform binary division operation on the received data.
    3) If the remainder of the division is ZERO accept data (data is not corrupted). If remainder is Non-ZERO reject data (data is corrupted).

    Page 1 of 8

    Experiment#13

    Capture packets using Wireshark, write the exact packet capture filter expressions to accomplish the

    following and save the output in file:

    1. Capture all TCP traffic to/from Facebook, during the time when you log in to your Facebook account

    2. Capture all HTTP traffic to/from Facebook, when you log in to your Facebook account

    3. Write a DISPLAY filter expression to count all TCP packets (captured under item #1) that have the

    flags SYN, PSH, and RST set. Show the fraction of packets that had each flag set.

    4. Count how many TCP packets you received from / sent to Face book, and how many of each were

    also HTTP packets.

    Wireshark Overview

    Wireshark is a free, open-source network protocol analyzer that allows users to capture and analyze

    network traffic in real-time. It is widely used by network administrators, cybersecurity experts, and

    developers for troubleshooting, security analysis, and network performance monitoring.

    Key Features:

    Packet Capture: Wireshark captures live traffic from a network interface (e.g., Ethernet, Wi-Fi) and

    saves it for detailed analysis.

    Protocol Analysis: It supports the analysis of thousands of network protocols such as TCP, UDP,

    HTTP, DNS, and others.

    Filtering: Filters help focus on specific traffic, whether at the time of capture (capture filters) or

    during analysis (display filters).

    Visualization: It provides detailed, multi-layered packet inspection, showing the contents of each

    packet and its protocol stack.

    Exporting Data: The captured data can be saved in various formats such as PCAP, and reports can

    be generated.

    Why Use Wireshark?

    Troubleshooting Network Issues: Diagnosing problems like slow connections, dropped packets,

    or faulty protocols.

    Security Analysis: Monitoring traffic for suspicious behavior, detecting intrusions or

    vulnerabilities.

    Page 2 of 8

    Learning Tool: Understanding how networks and protocols operate in detail.

    Wireshark is widely respected for its powerful capabilities, providing insights into network behaviour by

    breaking down traffic into its smallest components, the packets.

    Summary

    Wireshark is a powerful tool for capturing and analysing network traffic.

    Capture filters are applied before packet capture to narrow down relevant traffic.

    Display filters are used post-capture to analyse specific aspects of traffic.

    Installing Wireshark on Ubuntu OS

    Use following commands to install Wireshark on Ubuntu OS.

    Use following command to run Wireshark.

    Page 3 of 8

    1. Capture all TCP traffic to/from Facebook, during the time when you log in to your Facebook

    account

    Capture Filter Expression

    tcp and(host facebook.com or host www.facebook.com)

    This filter captures all TCP traffic to or from Facebook's main domain. You should replace

    facebook.com with Facebook's IP addresses (e.g.31.13.79.35) if DNS resolution is not available during

    capture. You can find the IP addresses using a ping or nslookup command.

    Page 1 of 2

    Experiment#15

    To study the SSL protocol by capturing the packets using Wireshark tool while visiting any SSL secured

    website (banking, e-commerce etc.).

    To capture packets related to SSL/TLS protocol using Wireshark while visiting an SSL-secured website

    (such as banking or e-commerce), you can use the following filter expressions:

    1. Basic SSL/TLS Packet Capture Filter

    This filter captures all SSL and TLS traffic.

    ssl or tls

    This expression will capture any SSL or TLS traffic between your device and the website you are visiting.

    2. Filter for Traffic Over HTTPS (SSL/TLS on Port 443)

    This filter captures traffic over port 443, which is commonly used for HTTPS communication.

    tcp.port == 443

    This will capture all traffic going to and from port 443, which is typically used for SSL/TLS connections.

    Page 2 of 2

    3. Filter for Specific IP Address

    To capture SSL traffic only between your machine and a specific server, you can filter by the IP address of

    the website.

    ip.addr == <server_ip_address> and tls
